---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { RoundtableTree } from "../components/RoundtableTree";
import { ROUNDTABLE } from "../lib/personas";
import { u } from "../lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Roundtable"
  description="Four personas, two rounds, one product question. The proposed library was killed and rebuilt by the cross-examination."
  wave="roundtable"
>
  <main class="roundtable">
    <div class="tracked">Wave 2 · The Roundtable</div>
    <h1>Four personas. Two rounds. One product killed.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      The agents drafted a Python library — two-tier mutable storage, a "git for agent context" pitch. Then the four-persona roundtable refused it. Round 1: independent takes. Round 2: each persona forced to address one other's R1 take — dismantle, steelman, or move toward it.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Topic.</em> {ROUNDTABLE.topic}
    </p>
    <p>
      Of all the agents in this session, the four roundtable personas (and their R2 doubles) are the only ones that loaded the full persona-skill profile rather than a prompt-level primer. <a href={u("/agents")}>How that worked.</a>
    </p>

    <RoundtableTree client:load />

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>What survived</h2>
    <p>
      The roundtable converged on a sharper architecture: <strong>an immutable append-only event log with importance and confidence as pure functions over the log</strong>. Tier membership is a view, not a stored place. Different scorers can be A/B'd against the same historical events — deterministically replayable, swappable, debuggable.
    </p>
    <p>
      That architecture is what the <a href={u("/observatory")}>Observatory</a> primitive ships. The benchmark on that page measures its central claims under multi-seed conditions — and surfaces a real failure mode of imperfect importance signals that the pure-function design lets you diagnose cleanly.
    </p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
